## VII. ARCHITECT'S STRATEGIC RECOMMENDATIONS

*My read on what matters most right now, based on everything in the codebase and design docs.*

### Recommendation 1: IDX-006 (Rubber Band) Before Anything Else
**Highest priority.** Without it, the `position` field on [IdeologyComponent](file:///c:/Users/zephy/Documents/Brinkmanship/brinkmanship_engine/src/state.rs#26-51) is cosmetic. Any scenario we script for NAR-001 would have no mechanical teeth — the player can just press buttons without consequence. The Rubber Band is what makes the Structural Matrix a **constraint system** rather than a label system. It's also relatively small: ~30 lines in [reactor.rs](file:///c:/Users/zephy/Documents/Brinkmanship/brinkmanship_engine/src/reactor.rs) or [chronos.rs](file:///c:/Users/zephy/Documents/Brinkmanship/brinkmanship_engine/src/chronos.rs) checking if the requested position delta exceeds the Overton Spread and applying a Chaos Modifier if so.

### Recommendation 2: Port [merge_scenarios.py](file:///c:/Users/zephy/Documents/Brinkmanship/merge_scenarios.py) to Rust Next
**Quick win, clears the Python question permanently.** It's a ~50-line script that merges JSON scenario files. Porting it to a Rust function tested in the journey suite is fast and gets us to a point where we can confidently answer *"yes, the Python code is fully deprecated."* It's been on the backlog for two sprints.

### Recommendation 3: Wire [flavor_label](file:///c:/Users/zephy/Documents/Brinkmanship/brinkmanship_engine/src/ideology_matrix.rs#98-123) to the UI [IdeologyCompass.tsx](file:///c:/Users/zephy/Documents/Brinkmanship/ui/src/app/components/IdeologyCompass.tsx)
**High visual payoff for almost zero engine work.** The [flavor_label](file:///c:/Users/zephy/Documents/Brinkmanship/brinkmanship_engine/src/ideology_matrix.rs#98-123) field is already being stored in state and serialized via Axum. The UI just needs to render it as the government title. This is a 1-session frontend task and will make the simulation *feel* dramatically more alive — watching the title change from *"Liberal Democracy"* → *"Third Way"* → *"Managed Democracy"* as you govern is the single most tangible demonstration of the Structural Matrix to a new player or stakeholder.

### Recommendation 4: Defer DIP-002 (AI Parity) Until IDX-006/007 Are Done
**Strategic patience.** Rival AI actors are powerful but pointless if they can jump across the matrix freely. The AI Director should be built *on top of* the Rubber Band and Glacial Shift physics — otherwise we're coding around a broken foundation. Build the physics, then give rivals an AI that operates within them.

### Recommendation 5: Consider a [scenarios/](file:///c:/Users/zephy/Documents/Brinkmanship/brinkmanship_engine/src/main.rs#249-253) Refactor Before NAR-001
**Narrative readiness.** The tutorial (NAR-001) will require scripted scenario files that set initial faction/estate compositions and starting grid positions. The current [scenarios/](file:///c:/Users/zephy/Documents/Brinkmanship/brinkmanship_engine/src/main.rs#249-253) folder has 7 JSON files but no schema validation. Before scripting "The Persian Gulf Crisis," we should define a canonical scenario schema (in [state.rs](file:///c:/Users/zephy/Documents/Brinkmanship/brinkmanship_engine/src/state.rs) or a new `scenario.rs`) so the tutorial files are statically typed and testable — not loose JSON that breaks silently.

---

### The Honest Gap

The current test suite validates **individual components in isolation**: the Overton math, the friction formula, the zone gate logic. What we do not yet have is a test that simulates a **sequence of sovereign decisions across multiple ticks** — enact a policy, watch `position` drift, watch faction influence shift reactively, watch a zone gate activate, watch an estate rebel. That 10-tick behavioral test is the true north star for journey testing and should be the culmination of IDX-006 and IDX-007 implementation.

---

*"The transition to a Living Simulation requires systemic physics, not just branching narrative."*
